TI  - Autonomous multi-robot synthesis and optimization of metal halide perovskite nanocrystals
AU  - Jinge Xu
AU  - Christopher H. J. Moran
AU  - Arup Ghorai
AU  - Fazel Bateni
AU  - Jeffrey A. Bennett
AU  - Nikolai Mukhin
AU  - Koray Latif
AU  - Andrew Cahn
AU  - Pragyan Jha
AU  - Fernando Delgado Licona
AU  - Sina Sadeghi
AU  - Lior Politi
AU  - Milad Abolhasani
T2  - Nature Communications
AB  - Metal halide perovskite (MHP) nanocrystals (NCs) offer extraordinary tunability in their optical properties, yet fully exploiting this potential is challenged by a vast and complex synthesis parameter space. Herein, we introduce Rainbow, a multi-robot self-driving laboratory that integrates automated NC synthesis, real-time characterization, and machine learning (ML)-driven decision-making to efficiently navigate MHP NCs' mixed-variable high-dimensional landscape. Using parallelized, miniaturized batch reactors, robotic sample handling, and continuous spectroscopic feedback, Rainbow autonomously optimizes MHP NC optical performance-including photoluminescence quantum yield and emission linewidth at a targeted emission energy-through closed-loop experimentation. By systematically exploring varying ligand structures and precursor conditions, Rainbow elucidates critical structure-property relationships and identifies scalable Pareto-optimal formulations for targeted spectral outputs. Rainbow provides a versatile blueprint for accelerated, data-driven discovery and retrosynthesis of high-performance metal halide perovskite nanocrystals, facilitating the on-demand realization of next-generation photonic materials and technologies.
